<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANTELOPE VALLEY WINS BY SHUTOUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE ELLING, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gee, thanks. 
</P>
<P>
 So West Bakersfield High marched up and down the field as often as not. So the 
Vikings rolled up a respectable dose of yardage. So they pushed the Antelope 
Valley defense around several times. 
</P>
<P>
 So . . . what? 
</P>
<P>
 West couldn't protect the football, and basically handed Antelope Valley a 
14-0 victory in an intersectional game Friday night at Antelope Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 West (1-1) didn't have any trouble cranking up its offense, especially in the 
first half, but forked the ball over four times, including a game-deciding 
fumble at the Antelope Valley two-yard line with 2 minutes 41 seconds 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
 "They just didn't hold onto the ball," said Antelope Valley quarterback Trymon 
Redick, who also plays in the secondary. " Toooooo many turnovers." 
</P>
<P>
 With less than three minutes left, West drove to the Antelope Valley eight, 
but two running plays only moved the ball to the two. On third down, reserve 
running back Cory Oggs fumbled at the two and Redick recovered. 
</P>
<P>
 It marked the second consecutive shutout for Antelope Valley (2-0), which 
defeated Hesperia last week, 8-0. West outgained Antelope Valley, 225-201, but 
without the ball, it doesn't mean much. 
</P>
<P>
 "It might have been closer without the turnovers," said Antelope Valley 
running back Jermaine Lewis, who was held to 58 yards in 18 carries, but scored 
on a seven-yard run with 4:05 left in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 With Antelope Valley holding a two-touchdown lead in the final quarter, West 
mounted another scoring threat, but it ended when quarterback Kyle Ursery was 
sacked by a trio of players on fourth and 17 at the Antelopes' 32 with 10:09 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
 With the defense making the fortuitous play, it didn't matter that Antelope 
Valley also was blanked in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
 Antelope Valley took a 14-0 lead with six seconds remaining in the first half 
when Ken Nelson scored on a one-yard run, and Redick ran a bootleg for the 
two-point conversion. 
</P>
<P>
 Antelope Valley sophomore Tony Walker had recovered a fumble at the West 41 
with 2:05 left. On the ensuing series, he turned a screen pass in a long gain 
gain that ended inside the one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
